, illustrative context – Russian poetry – both changed and remained constant? An Indwelling Voice grapples, uniquely, with such questions. In case studies ranging from the late neoclassical period to post-postmodernism, it explores how Russian poets have generated the pragmatic framings and poetic devices that allow them to inscribe sincere voices in their poetry. Engaging Anglo-American and European literature, as well as providing close readings of Russian poetry, An Indwelling Voice helps us understand how poets have at times generated a powerful sense of presence, intimating that they speak through the poem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAuthenticity (Philosophy) in literature. 0aRomanticismzRussia. 0aRussian poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSincerity in literature. 7aPOETRY / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aAlexander Pushkin.  aAnna Akhmatova.  aApollon Grigoryev.  aDmitry Venevitinov.  aMikhail Lermontov.  aRussian poetry.  aauthenticity.  ahistory of lyric poetry.  aliterary studies.  asincere voice.  asincerity.  atheory of the lyric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z978311131826408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754457740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487544577423Coveruht